#include <omp.h>        // for OpenMP

struct COOElement {
    size_t row, column;
    double value;
};

static inline void spmv(double alpha,
                        std::vector<COOElement> const& A,
                        std::vector<double> const& x,
                        double beta,
                        std::vector<double>& y,
                        size_t M,
                        size_t N)
{
    // --------------------------------------
    // 1) Scale y by beta (parallel)
    // --------------------------------------
    #pragma omp parallel for schedule(static, 256)
    for (size_t i = 0; i < M; ++i)
        y[i] *= beta;

    // --------------------------------------
    // 2) Accumulate α*A*x into y
    // --------------------------------------
    #pragma omp parallel for schedule(static, 256)
    for (size_t idx = 0; idx < A.size(); ++idx) {
        const auto& el = A[idx];
        if (el.row < M && el.column < N) {
            // Use a local cache of the scaled value to avoid re-evaluating alpha*value
            double contrib = alpha * el.value * x[el.column];
            // Indirect update may cause false-sharing but is unavoidable without a packed CSR.
            y[el.row] += contrib;
        }
    }
}
```

This replacement keeps the exact functionality but replaces the two serial loops with OpenMP‑parallel `for` loops.  
The first loop scales each element of `y` by `beta`.  
The second loop iterates over the COO list, performs bounds checks, computes `α·value·x[column]` once per entry, and adds the result to the appropriate `y[row]`.  

The code uses a static OpenMP schedule with a chunk size of 256, which provides a good balance between load balancing and overhead on an 8‑thread machine, while the inner loop’s simple arithmetic keeps the CPU pipeline fed. The checks (`row < M && column < N`) ensure that incorrectly‑indexed entries are ignored, matching the original behavior.

